  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">MERF Maradi Emergency Response to Nigerian Refugee Influx</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Growing insecurity in Sokoto and Zamfara states in northwestern Nigeria, bordering Niger, has resulted in the cross border displacement of roughly 20,000 Nigerian refugees. The displacements started in Zamfara at low levels in the late summer of 2018 as a result of criminality and unrest. In April and May 2019, the numbers spiralled as thousands of Nigerians fled to Niger from neigbouring Sokoto State, fleeing rampant kidnapping, banditry, sexual violence and killings. The violence is generally (though not excusively) thought to be caused by a combination of inter-communal violence and banditry, rather than the violent jihadism wihch characterizes North-East Nigeria. The Nigerian states of Sokoto and Zamfara from which the displaced populations originate is hard to reach and has few humanitarian actors on the ground, so reliable information on the violence there is hard to find (source: REACH Rapid Briefing Note: Niger &#x2013; Maradi, 27 June, 2019).</narrative>
  </description>
